# base.word — the first words, the floor of the vocabulary.
# Their MEANING bottoms out in the host (as the kernel is the floor of the behavior, 9.md §2);
# DECLARING them makes them recognized words every concept above can lean on. The grammar
# (is, a, an, has, can, of) and the bare relations (before, after, in, over) stay
# the irreducible syntax, not words. Every word here was checked against the declared verbs,
# ops, and concepts for collision: `set` was dropped (it is the verb); these five are clean.

One is a single, not many. One act makes one fact.

An order is words, each before or after another.

A head is the last in an order.

Content is a word's body.

A hash is the seal over content and all before it. One content, after one history, makes one hash, and no other content or history makes it. As a sign marks who made a word, a hash marks what a word is.
